the First World War, it rereads the development of Giorgio de Chirico’s Metaphysical art and Massimo Bontempelli’s Realismo Magico. The book reconstructs the multimedia archive of the Fascist initiatives for the 1933 centennial anniversary of Ariosto’s death, and then focuses on the passage between Fascist cinema and the birth of neorealism, unearthing unfinished adaptations of the Orlando Furioso by Luchino Visconti and Alessandro Blasetti. Questioning the very concept of reception, this radically interdisciplinary book warns twenty-first-century readers about the risks of monumentalizing the "great authors" of the past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aArt and literaturezItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictures and literaturezItalyxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Italian.2bisacsh  aFascist culture.  aFerrara.  aGiorgio de Chirico.  aItalian studies.  aItaly.  aLudovico Ariosto.  aOrlando Furioso.  aRenaissance literature.  aepic poetry.  afilm adaptation.  amagical realism.  ametaphysical art.  areception.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023 Englishz978311131918608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023z978311131826408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079736740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754681640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487546816423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/docum